Third-party code
----------------

Edda is an original, self-hosting language. Everything published in this
repository — the compiler (written in Edda), the std.* standard library, the
ecosystem packages, the first-party applications, and the codex specification
(prose) — is original work authored for this project. No third-party source
code is vendored, embedded, or copied into this repository: the tree contains
no external source files and no files carrying a separate license, copyright
notice, or attribution header.

The primitives implemented in Edda in this repository — the hash functions
under std/lib/crypto/hash (BLAKE3, SHA-256, SHA-512), the HMAC constructions
under std/lib/crypto/mac, std/lib/core/checksum, and the byte encodings under
std/lib/encoding (ASN.1, base32/64, hex, percent/URL, UTF-16, varint) — are
original Edda implementations written against public specifications: IETF
RFCs, NIST FIPS and Special Publications, and the published definitions of the
respective algorithms. Standard constants reproduced from those documents
(initialization vectors, S-boxes, round constants, and named elliptic-curve
domain parameters) are facts drawn from public standards and are not
themselves subject to copyright. These implementations are covered by the dual
MIT OR Apache-2.0 grant above and carry no additional third-party license
terms.

The remaining cryptographic surfaces — AEAD ciphers, elliptic-curve and RSA
signatures and encryption, ECDH, HKDF, X.509 and PEM parsing, constant-time
helpers, randomness (under std/lib/crypto), and std/lib/math/bigint — are
declared in this repository as Edda extern interfaces: original function and
type declarations bound to runtime symbols. The implementations behind those
symbols are supplied at link time by the toolchain's runtime library, built
and distributed from the separate bootstrap-compiler repository. That runtime
satisfies them with established third-party Rust cryptography libraries (the
RustCrypto project's crates and the dalek-cryptography crates), consumed there
as ordinary declared dependencies under their own licenses (Apache-2.0 OR MIT,
and BSD-3-Clause respectively) — never vendored, copied, or transliterated
into either repository. Distributions that bundle a linked runtime carry those
projects' license notices alongside the runtime's own distribution materials.

The build-time, content-addressed hashing used by the bootstrap toolchain
itself likewise relies on the upstream BLAKE3 Rust crate under that crate's
own license in the bootstrap repository; it is not redistributed here.

